g.text: The Momento design pattern violates the DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) principle. The Momento contains a copy of the internals of the Originator. This means changes in the internals of the Originator will most probably also reflect on the Momento. However, this is still an improvement as opposed to exposing the Originator internals directly to its clients. E.g.: changing the datatype of the internal state of the Originator could reflect on multiple clients. In case of the Momento design pattern the impact is minimized to just the Momento.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The Momento design pattern enables capturing the internal sta...

g.text: The Momento design pattern enables capturing the internal state of an object (=Originator) while preserving encapsulation. The Originator constructs the Momento (=Token) by passing its internal state. This construction happens when the Caretaker (=client) requires a snapshot of the Originator state. The Momento exposes a narrow interface towards the Caretakers to preserve encapsulation. A wide interface is exposed towards its Originator. Only the Originator can get and set the internals of the Momento. The Caretaker may only see some meta data of the Momento. Applicability of the Momento Design pattern are undo or rollback mechanisms (e.g. GIT stash).

g.title: Folded Corner.258
g.desc: The Momento pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Pri...

g.text: The Momento pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Principle by preserving encapsulation of the Originator and delegating Momento storage management to the Caretaker. Encapsulation ensures extendibility, safety and restriction of the code. All aspects are compared against an implementation where Originator exposes its internals and fulfills snapshot management. Extendibility (or changeability), because the Caretaker is not dependent on the Originator’s internals directly, but communicates via a defined, narrow interface. The Caretaker requires a copy of the (partial) internal state of the Originator. The Originator is not forced to expose its internals to the Caretaker and break its encapsulation. The Originator uses the Momento instead, that provides a narrow interface towards the Caretaker. This makes changing the Originator less impactful, because coupling between Caretaker and Originator is degraded. Safety and restriction, because the Caretaker or other clients are unable to manipulate the state of the Originator freely. This overcomes unforeseen data manipulation (e.g. quick fixes of developers) that may result in bugs or crashes later. The Momento design pattern forces design into this restricted direction. The Originator delegates storage management of the snapshots to the Caretaker. The Originator could maintain snapshots of its internal state. However, this would increase the complexity of the Originator.
